From: Heiko Gleu <heiko_gleu@web.de>
Subject: [PATCH] rkcommon: guard `nan` macro to ISPC context only

The header `rkcommon/math/math.ih` defines `nan` as a preprocessor macro
that expands to `floatbits(0x7FBFFFFF)`. This is fine for ISPC code, but
the same header is also pulled into C++ translation units (e.g. by
OpenVKL's GPU device sources). On systems with glibc >= 2.43 (Ubuntu
26.04), `<bits/mathcalls.h>` declares `nan(...)` as a function via the
`__MATHCALL` macro family. The macro expansion of OUR `nan` then mangles
those declarations and produces hundreds of bizarre errors:

    error: redefinition of 'floatbits' as different kind of symbol
    error: pasting formed ')f', an invalid preprocessing token
    error: redeclaration of '__floatbits' with a different type

The ISPC `nan` macro is not actually needed in C++ context (only `inf`,
`pos_inf`, `neg_inf` are used), so guard it under `#ifdef ISPC`.

Apply to: <install-prefix>/rkcommon/include/rkcommon/math/math.ih

---
diff --git a/rkcommon/math/math.ih b/rkcommon/math/math.ih
--- a/rkcommon/math/math.ih
+++ b/rkcommon/math/math.ih
@@ -30,7 +30,9 @@
 #define inf floatbits(0x7F800000)
 #define pos_inf floatbits(0x7F800000)
 #define neg_inf floatbits(0xFF800000)
-#define nan floatbits(0x7FBFFFFF)
+#ifdef ISPC
+#define nan floatbits(0x7FBFFFFF)
+#endif
 // smallest positive normal number 2^-126 ~ 1.17549435e-38
 #define flt_min 0x1.0p-126f
